Setup

If you have not installed the following packages, please install before loading them.

library(readxl)
library(tidyverse)
library(haven) #for loading other datafiles (SAS, STATA, SPSS, etc.)
knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE)

Challenge Overview

This first weekly challenge aims to practice the following skill sets: 1. Read datasets in different file types; 2. Describe the datasets; 3. Exploring a few basic functions of data transformation and wrangling; and 4. Present some descriptive statistics.

There will be coding components (reading datasets and data transformation) and writing components (describing the datasets and some statistical information). Please read the instructions for each part and complete your challenges.

Creating your own R quarto project and make sure your working directory

(Will be demonstrated on Sep 20 and 21 lab meetings)

Baby Names Dataset (Required)

  1. Read the dataset “babynames.csv”:
#Type your code here
  babynamesData <- read_csv("./babynames.csv")
  head(babynamesData)

  1. Data Description: Please use the necessary commands and codes and briefly describe this data with a short writing paragraph answering the following questions.

    dim(babynamesData)
    [1] 2084710       4

    (1) What is the dimension of the data (# of rows and columns)? 1A: The dimension of the data is 2084710 rows and 4 columns

    (2) What do the rows and columns mean in this data? 2A: The rows in this data represents a name in a given year and column names are different variables: Name, Sex, Occurences and Year

    (3) What is the unit of observation? In other words, what does each case mean in this data? 3A: Each case in this data mean each baby name and their relative information

    (4) According to the lecture, is this “tidy” data? 4A: Yes this is a tidy data as the data is structured in a table with rows and columns and ready it to be analyzed and visualized, each column is a variable and each row is an observation ’

  2. Data Transformation: use necessary commands and codes and answer the following questions.

Optional 1: European Social Survey Dataset

  1. Read the dataset “ESS_5.dta”.

    european_survey <- read_dta("./ESS_5.dta")

  1. Data Description: Please use the necessary commands and codes and briefly describe this data with a short writing paragraph answering the following questions.

    (1) What is the dimension of the data (# of rows and columns)? 1A: The dimension of the data: 52458 rows, 696 columns

    dim(european_survey)
    [1] 52458   696

    As we can see, this data is very large. We don’t want to study the whole data. Let’s just reload the following selected columns: idno, essroud, male, age, edu, income_10, eth_major, media (a standardized measure of the frequency of media consumption), and cntry.

    #selecting only specific columns
  european_survey_data<-select(european_survey,c(1:8),11)
  european_survey_data

    (2) For the reloaded data, what do the rows and columns mean in this data? 2A: Each row gives an observation and each column is a variable (3) What is the unit of observation? In other words, what does each case mean in this data? 3A: Unit of observation: Respondents details including country, education,
    sex,age and income

    (4) According to the lecture, is this a “tidy” data? 4A: Yes this is a tidy data as the data is structured in a table with rows and columns and ready it to be analyzed and visualized, each column is a variable and each row is an observation

  2. Data Transformation: use necessary commands and codes and answer the following questions.

Optional 2: Polity V Data

  1. Read the dataset “p5v2018.sav”.

polity_data <- read_sav("./p5v2018.sav")

  1. Data Description: Please use the necessary commands and codes and briefly describe this data with a short writing paragraph answering the following questions.

    #using dim() to get dimension of data
dim(polity_data)
    [1] 17574    37

    (1) What is the dimension of the data (# of rows and columns)? The dimension of the polity data table are 17574 rows and 37 columns

    As we can see, this data contains many columns. We don’t want to study the whole data. Let’s keep the first seven columns and the eighth and ninth columns.

    #selecting columns from 1-7 and 9,10
polity_dataset <- polity_data[,c(1:7,9,10)]
head(polity_dataset)
    dim(polity_dataset)
    [1] 17574     9

    (2) For the reloaded data, what do the rows mean in this data? What do the columns (#2-#8) mean? The columns #2-#8 give information about the calender year,country code,country name, flag, democracy scale and autocracy scale

    (3) What is the unit of observation? In other words, what does each case mean in this data? Unit of observation: polity5(p5) score of countries each year

    (4) According to the lecture, is this a “tidy” data? Yes, this is a tidy data as every column is a variable and every row is an observation

Railraod Employee Data

  1. Read the dataset “railroads.xls”.

    Many government organizations still use Excel spreadsheet to store data. This railraod dataset, publisehd by the Railroad Retirement Board, is a typical example. It records the number of employees in each county and state in 2012.

    Please load the data in R in a clean manner. You can start with doing the following things step by step.

    (1) Read the first sheet of the excel file;

    (2) Skipping the title rows;

    (3) Removing empty columns

    (4) Filtering “total” rows

    (5) Remove the table notes (the last two rows)

      #skip the first three rows 
   railroad<-read_excel("./railroads.xls", sheet = 1, skip = 3)

railroad_clean<-railroad [-c( 2, 9, 77, 79, 152, 168, 224, 282, 291, 293,
                              297, 365, 518, 522, 622, 659, 763, 856, 952, 1072,
                              1136, 1149, 1174, 1191, 1270, 1357, 1473, 1552, 1606, 1701,
                          1751, 1841, 1852, 1874, 1904, 1917, 1979, 2068, 2142, 2176,
                          2242, 2248, 2295, 2348, 2440, 2662, 2688, 2781, 2796, 2836,
                          2906, 2960, 2983:2990
                          ),-c(2,4) #skip the empty columns
                          ]


head(railroad_clean)

  1. Data Description: Please use the necessary commands and codes and briefly describe this data with a short writing paragraph answering the following questions.

    #Type your code here; and write a paragraph answering the questions.
 railroad_str<-read_excel("./railroads.xls", sheet = 1,
                     skip = 4,
                     col_names= c("State", "delete", "County", "delete", "Employees"))|>
  select(!contains("delete"))|>
  filter(!str_detect(State, "Total"))
railroad_str<-railroad_str[-c(2991:2993),]

head(railroad_str)
    dim(railroad_clean)
    [1] 2930    3

    (1) What is the dimension of the data (# of rows and columns)? 1A: Dimension: 2932 rows, 3 columns

    (2) What do the rows and columns mean? 2A: Rows give the information about state and county wise total railroads Column are State(character), County(character) and Total(numeric) variables

    (3) What is the unit of observation? In other words, what does each case mean in this data? 3A: A unit of observation in this data is a county.

    (4) According to the lecture, is this a “tidy” data? 4A: Yes, this is a tidy data as every column is a variable and every row is an observation’

  2. Data Transformation: use necessary commands and codes and answer the following questions.

    #2.n_distinct(): an extension from the function distinct()
railroad_clean|>
  summarise(across(c(STATE, COUNTY), n_distinct))
    ##Total number of employees
railroad_clean|>
  summarise(total_employees = sum(TOTAL))
    ##Statistics
railroad_clean|>
  summarise(min = min(TOTAL), max = max(TOTAL), mean = mean(TOTAL), median = median(TOTAL))
    ##Getting the county and state with the most employees
railroad_clean|>
  group_by(STATE)|>
  summarise(total_employees = sum(TOTAL))|>
  arrange(desc(total_employees))
    railroad_clean|>
  group_by(COUNTY)|>
  summarise(total_employees = sum(TOTAL))|>
  arrange(desc(total_employees))
    #but in fact, there are two Cook Counties in the data! 

##Solution 1: Group by County and State

railroad_clean|>
  ungroup()
    railroad_clean|>
  group_by(COUNTY, STATE)|>
  summarise(total_employees = sum(TOTAL))|>
  arrange(desc(total_employees))
    ##Solution 2: Group by County and State
##Since county is the unit of observation in this data, we can simply rank the dataset without specifying grouping.
railroad_clean|>
  ungroup()
    railroad_clean %>% arrange(desc(TOTAL))

    (1) How many unique counties and states are in the data? (tips: you can try using the across() function to do an operation on two columns at the same time) 1A: There are 53 states and 1709 counties in this data. (If including Canada, there would be 54 states and 1709 counties).

    (2) What is the total number of employees (total_employees) in this data? 2A: 255423 (or 256085 including Canada).

    (3) What is the min, max, mean, and median of “total_employees” 3A: Min: 1, Max: 8207, Mean: 87.17816, Median: 21

    (4) Which states have the most employees? And which countries have the most employees? (tips: use group_by() and arrange()) 4A: Texas (19839) and Cook County of Illinois (8207) have the most employees.
